<p class="EnTeteTranscription">McKenzie, Alexander. Journal of Great Bear Lake, 1805-1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0006</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">June 16<sup>th</sup></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">frose.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey often make their meal without fier<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>heir Dress is much the same as the red Knives but not so cleanly and the men &amp; woman wear their hair without Cutting any part of it<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The Hare Indians is suposed to be 300 men of which only 115 have been at our trading posts<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey are a very Indolent set<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey Kill very little Beaver<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>heir prinsipal hunt is martins &amp; muskrats<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[I]</span>t tis only three years since they have had traders amongst them<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey amuse themselves with taking fish and Hares<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>he prinsiple of their Cloathing is made with the Skin of the Hare<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>he Womans Robes or frocks is Lased <span class="AddHand-author">b</span>efore and very short<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>t their Camps they are amongst the men without much seremony<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey show all their shapes<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The men has a small Leather tassel hanging before his private parts, which I supose is only ornament for his all is visible.  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hey set snares for Carriboux and the musk Buffaloe of which they take great numbers<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="AddHand-editors">[June]</span> 17</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">At 10 O Clock in the morning I left the Fort with the Farroe a Montineer to go to the Enterence of Bear River<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We embarked on the Ice at a mile from the Fort<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>e found that the Ice was 6 feet thick<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Lepratt one of my men had cut his Leg with an ax very badly not able to walk<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I had the Cannoes Loaded at 3 O Clock and Embarked we shipped a good deal of watter<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I made them put on shore and only left four Men per Cannoe<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>he others with M<sup>r</sup> G. and myself walked about four miles when we encamped not being able to go further for Ice<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>hree men from the Forks of M<sup>c</sup>Kenzies River arrived and informed me that they had left the cannoes at the Enterence of the River<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> that they could not bring them up for the Ice and that they had lost one of their men since 12 O Clock about 3 miles below and had remained in serch of him all day without finding him<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="AddHand-editors">[June]</span> 18<sup>th</sup></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">I sent two Indians in serche of the lost man<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[A]</span>ll the Packs &amp;ca was well Covered and sent M<sup>r</sup> Grant with all the men to the Fort as they could live there on fish</p>
